# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetone
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was first reported by Henri Victor Regnault in 1840.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Industrially, it is usually produced in a two-step process from vinyl chloride.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction is catalyzed by a variety of Lewis acids, mainly aluminium chloride, iron(III) chloride, or zinc chloride.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction proceeds at 80%–90% yield, and the hydrogen chloride byproduct can be recycled to the first step in the process.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The major side-product is the related compound 1,1,2-trichloroethane, from which the 1,1,1-trichloroethane can be separated by distillation.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is sold with stabilizers because it is unstable with respect to dehydrochlorination and attacks some metals.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Stabilizers comprise up to 8% of the formulation, including acid scavengers (epoxides, amines) and complexants.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] One discontinued product contained only 1,4-dioxane (2%±1%), while another chemical supplier included 2.5% 1,4-dioxane, 0.47% 1,2-butylene oxide, and 0.35% nitromethane as stabilizers.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is an excellent solvent for many organic compounds and one of the least toxic of the chlorinated hydrocarbons.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is generally considered non-polar, but owing to the good polarizability of the chlorine atoms, it is a superior solvent for organic compounds that do not dissolve well in hydrocarbons such as hexane.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Prior to the Montreal Protocol, it was widely used for cleaning metal parts and circuit boards, as a photoresist solvent in the electronics industry, as an aerosol propellant, as a cutting fluid additive, and as a solvent for inks, paints, adhesives, and other coatings.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used to dry-clean leather and suede.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Use in dry-cleaning remained until the 1980s.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used as an insecticidal fumigant.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also the standard cleaner for photographic film.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Other commonly available solvents damage emulsion and base (acetone will dissolve triacetate base on most films), and thus are not suitable for this application.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The standard replacement, Forane 141 is much less effective, and tends to leave a residue.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also used as a thinner in correction fluid products such as liquid paper.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Many of its applications previously used carbon tetrachloride (which was banned in US consumer products in 1970).
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In turn, 1,1,1-trichloroethane itself is now being replaced by other solvents in the laboratory.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Phase-out of 1,1,1-Trichloroethane due to ozone depletion lead to a resurgence of the use of trichloroethylene in metal degreasing.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Methyl chloroform was also used as a veterinary anthelmintic.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was one of the volatile organochlorides that have been tried as alternatives to chloroform in anaesthesia.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In the 1880s, it was found to be a safe and strong substitute for chloroform but its production was too expensive and difficult for the era.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In 1880, 1,1,1-trichloroethane was suggested as an anaesthetic.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was first referred to as methyl-chloroform in the same year.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] At the time, the narcotic effects of chloral hydrate were owed to a hypothetical metabolic pathway to chloroform in "alkaline blood".
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Trichloroethane was studied for its structural similarity to chloral and potential anaesthetic effects.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] However, trichloroethane did not exhibit any conversion to chloroform in laboratory experiments.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The 1,1,2-Trichloroethane (vinyl trichloride) isomer, which lacked a trichloromethyl group, exhibited anaesthetic effects even stronger than the 1,1,1 isomer.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The International Agency for Research on Cancer places 1,1,1-trichloroethane in Group 2A as a probable carcinogen.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is a fairly potent greenhouse gas with a 100-year global warming potential of 169 relative to carbon dioxide.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This is nonetheless less than a tenth that of carbon tetrachloride — which it replaced as a solvent — due to its relatively short atmospheric lifetime of about 5 years.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The Montreal Protocol targeted 1,1,1-trichloroethane as a compound responsible for ozone depletion and banned its use beginning in 1996.
[src:acetone/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Since then, its manufacture and use have been phased out throughout most of the world, and its atmospheric concentration has declined substantially.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:acetone/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:acetone/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:acetone/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:acetone/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The enzyme involved in making 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) is DXP synthase.
[src:acetone/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The mechanism follows a catalysis of decarboxylative condensation of pyruvate and d-glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate to produce DXP.
[src:acetone/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] In addition, the molecule is involved in making thiamine (vitamin B1) and pyridoxol (vitamin B6).
[src:acetone/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The non-mevalonate pathway intermediate 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) also acts as a precursor in making isoprenoids in many species such as bacteria, plants, and apicomplexan parasites, contributing to biological diversity.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] 1-Pentanol is prepared from 1-butene by hydroformylation followed by hydrogenation of the resulting pentanal.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] Pentanol can be prepared by fractional distillation of fusel oil.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] To reduce the use of fossil fuels, research is underway to develop cost-effective methods of producing (chemically identical) bio-pentanol with fermentation.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] The hydroxyl group (OH) is the active site of many reactions.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] The ester formed from 1-pentanol and butyric acid is pentyl butyrate, which has an apricot-like odor.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] The ester formed from 1-pentanol and acetic acid is amyl acetate (also called pentyl acetate), which has a banana-like odor.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] It is a precursor to dipentyl zinc dithiophosphates, which are used in froth flotation.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] In 2014, a study was conducted comparing the performance of diesel fuel blends with various proportions of pentanol as an additive.
[src:acetone/1-pentanol] While gaseous emissions increased with higher concentrations of pentanol, particulate emissions decreased.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] The compound was discovered by Gustave Chancel in 1853 by fractional distillation of fusel oil.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] He measured its boiling point at 96°C, correctly identified its empirical formula, studied some of its chemical properties and gave it two names: **propionic alcohol** and **hydrate of trityl**.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] After several unsuccessful attempts, it was synthesized independently and by two different routes by Eduard Linnemann and Carl Schorlemmer in 1868.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Fusel alcohols like 1-Propanol are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of 1-Propanol are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] 1-Propanol shows the normal reactions of a primary alcohol.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Thus it can be converted to alkyl halides; for example red phosphorus and iodine produce n-propyl iodide in 80% yield, while PCl3 with catalytic ZnCl2 gives n-propyl chloride.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Reaction with acetic acid in the presence of an H2SO4 catalyst under Fischer esterification conditions gives propyl acetate, while refluxing propanol overnight with formic acid alone can produce propyl formate in 65% yield.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Oxidation of 1-propanol with Na2Cr2O7 and H2SO4 gives a 36% yield of propionaldehyde, and therefore for this type of reaction higher yielding methods using PCC or the Swern oxidation are recommended.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Oxidation with chromic acid yields propionic acid.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is manufactured by catalytic hydrogenation of propionaldehyde.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Propionaldehyde is produced via the oxo process by hydroformylation of ethylene using carbon monoxide and hydrogen in the presence of a catalyst such as cobalt octacarbonyl or a rhodium complex.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Other proposed industrial processes include the two-step isomerization and hydrogenation of propylene oxide.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] A traditional laboratory preparation of 1-propanol involves treating *n*-propyl iodide with moist Ag2O.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] 1-Propanol can also be prepared via the hydrogenation of acrolein with metal catalysts.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] 1-Propanol is thought to be similar to ethanol in its effects on the human body, but 2 to 4 times more potent according to a study conducted on rabbits.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Many toxicology studies find oral acute LD50 ranging from 1.9 g/kg to 6.5 g/kg (compared to 7.06 g/kg for ethanol).
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Effects include alcoholic intoxication and high anion gap metabolic acidosis.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] As of 2011, one case of lethal poisoning was reported following oral ingestion of 500mL of 1-propanol.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] Due to a lack of long term data, the carcinogenicity of 1-propanol in humans is unknown.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] 1-Propanol has a high octane number and is suitable for use as engine fuel.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] However, propanol is too expensive to use as a motor fuel.
[src:acetone/1-propanol] The research octane number (RON) of propanol is 118, and the anti-knock index (AKI) is 108.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Diberal, unlike most barbiturates, can have convulsant actions.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] This is uncommon, as barbiturates typically enhance the function of GABA as allorestic modulators and agonists (at higher doses), therefore having anticonvulsant properties.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Depending on which isomer is used, it can have either convulsant or anticonvulsant actions.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] The different pharmacological profile between isomers is thought to be due to the differences in the formation of hydrogen bonds at the binding sites.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (+)-DMBB is the atypical enantiomer of diberal.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It is atypical in the means that it has convulsant action, unlike most barbiturate drugs.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Unlike (+)-DMBB, the (−)-isomer is similar to most barbiturates by having anticonvulsant action.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It has been found that administration of (−)-DMBB reverses the convulsant actions of (+)-DMBB.
[src:acetone/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (−)-DMBB is slightly more potent than pentobarbital in its depressant properties.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:acetone/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:acetone/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:acetone/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:acetone/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:acetone/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:acetone/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:acetone/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:acetone/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:acetone/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:acetone/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:acetone/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:acetone/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:acetone/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:acetone/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:acetone/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:acetone/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:acetone/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:acetone/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:acetone/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:acetone/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:acetone/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:acetone/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:acetone/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:acetone/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:acetone/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:acetone/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:acetone/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:acetone/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:acetone/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:acetone/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:acetone/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:acetone/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:acetone/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:acetone/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:acetone/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:acetone/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:acetone/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:acetone/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:acetone/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:acetone/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:acetone/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:acetone/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:acetone/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:acetone/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:acetone/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:acetone/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:acetone/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:acetone/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:acetone/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:acetone/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:acetone/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:acetone/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:acetone/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:acetone/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:acetone/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:acetone/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:acetone/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:acetone/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:acetone/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:acetone/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:acetone/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:acetone/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:acetone/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:acetone/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:acetone/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:acetone/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:acetone/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:acetone/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:acetone/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:acetone/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:acetone/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:acetone/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:acetone/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:acetone/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:acetone/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:acetone/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:acetone/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:acetone/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:acetone/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:acetone/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:acetone/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:acetone/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:acetone/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP is an essential metabolite in most pathogenic bacteria including *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* as well as in malaria parasites, but is absent from the human host.
[src:acetone/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP is the physiological activator ("phosphoantigen") for human Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells, the major γδ T cell population in peripheral blood.
[src:acetone/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] With a bioactivity of 0.1 nM it is 10,000-10,000,000 times more potent than any other natural compound, such as IPP or alkyl amines.
[src:acetone/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP functions in this capacity by binding the B30.2 domain of BTN3A1.
